{
  "doc_id": "43572",
  "text": "In the simplest model for actin-mediated tethering, interacting vesicles zipper up via actin cross-linking proteins and our demonstration that IQGAP2 can mediate lysosome/phagosome attachment in vitro supports such a model. IQGAP2 is a member of a family of actin cross-linking proteins that are conserved from yeast to humans [CITATION_1] . The principal features of IQGAP2 and its closest homolog, IQGAP1 (62% identical), include an N-terminal calponin homology domain (CHD) that can bind F-actin, four calmodulin-binding IQ motifs, and a GTPase-activating protein (GAP)-related domain (GRD) that can bind Cdc42 or Rac1. The C-terminus can mediate binding to E-cadherin and ␤-catenin and to microtubules via CLIP-170. Similar to other IQ motif proteins (Jurado et al., 1999) , IQGAPs bind calmodulin in the absence of Ca 2ϩ , but interactions are enhanced in the presence of Ca 2ϩ [CITATION_2] . Despite their GRD domains IQGAP1 and IQGAP2 have no GAP activity but stabilize the GTP-bound form of Cdc42 and Rac1 [CITATION_3] . Binding of GTP-Cdc42/Rac1 in turn is required for the ability of IQGAP1 to cross-link F-actin into bundles and gels [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] .",
